# Binary Counter

<catsoop-section>Introduction</catsoop-section>

Computers count in a special way using only 0 and 1 — this is called the binary system. Each 0 or 1 is called a bit. In this activity, you will make a Binary Counter that works by flipping paper flaps to show how numbers increase in binary. It's an easy and fun way to see how computers count and store data!

<catsoop-section>Materials Required</catsoop-section>

- Chart paper or cardboard (A4 size)
- 4–6 paper strips
- Glue, stapler, or tape
- Marker pens (black and red)
- Ruler and pencil
- Labels – Bit 1, Bit 2, Bit 3…

<catsoop-section>Instructions</catsoop-section>

1. **Make Bit Flaps:**
   Cut 4 or more paper strips. Write 0 on one side and 1 on the back side of each strip. These flaps will act as the bits.

2. **Attach the Flaps:**
   Paste or staple each strip on the chart paper so they can flip up and down. Arrange them side by side and label from right to left as Bit 0, Bit 1, Bit 2, Bit 3.

3. **Start Counting:**
   Begin with all showing 0 (0000).
   - Flip the rightmost bit (Bit 0) to 1 — you now have 0001 = 1.
   - Flip back Bit 0 to 0 and turn Bit 1 to 1 — 0010 = 2.
   - Continue flipping to count like this:

   $$0000 \rightarrow 0001 \rightarrow 0010 \rightarrow 0011 \rightarrow 0100 \rightarrow 0101 \rightarrow 0110 \rightarrow 0111 \rightarrow 1000$$

4. **Color Coding (Optional):**
   Color 0 side blue and 1 side red to show OFF and ON states clearly.

